  <mads:note type="source">Smith's Dictionary of Greek and Roman Biography and Mythology, Vol 1,
      1867, p. 55: "Afranius, L. a Roman comic poet, who lived at the beginning of the first century
      B.C....Afranius must have written a great many comedies, as the names and fragments of between
      twenty and thirty are still preserved.."</mads:note>
  <mads:note type="source">Brill's New Pauly: "Afranius, 4, Roman comic poet. According to the
      opinion of ancient literary criticism (Vell. Pat. 2,9,3; Quint. Inst. 10,1,100) the most
      important representative of the fabula togata, Roman comedy in Roman garb. Like both of the
      other toga poets ( Titinius and Quinctius Atta) A. was probably a born Roman...."St&#xE4;rk,
      Ekkehard (Leipzig). "Afranius." Brill's New Pauly. Antiquity volumes edited by: Hubert Cancik
      and Helmuth Schneider . Brill, 2009. Brill Online.</mads:note>
